    <innerclass refid="classEspUsbSerialJtag" prot="public">EspUsbSerialJtag</innerclass>
    <briefdescription>
<para>ESP32-S3 / -C3 / -C6 USB Serial/JTAG console wrapper. </para>
    </briefdescription>
    <detaileddescription>
<para>Concrete implementation of <computeroutput><ref refid="classBaseUsbSerialJtag" kindref="compound">BaseUsbSerialJtag</ref></computeroutput> for Espressif chips that embed the <bold>USB Serial/JTAG controller</bold> (see ESP-IDF <computeroutput>components/esp_driver_usb_serial_jtag/</computeroutput>). Internally calls <computeroutput>usb_serial_jtag_driver_install()</computeroutput> once and forwards reads/writes to <computeroutput>usb_serial_jtag_read_bytes()</computeroutput> / <computeroutput>usb_serial_jtag_write_bytes()</computeroutput>.</para>
<para><simplesect kind="par"><title>Why a wrapper?</title><para>Application code in <computeroutput>main/</computeroutput> MUST NOT include <computeroutput>driver/usb_serial_jtag.h</computeroutput> directly — that would leak <computeroutput>esp_err_t</computeroutput>, <computeroutput>TickType_t</computeroutput>, and FreeRTOS into MCU-agnostic layers. By owning the driver behind <computeroutput><ref refid="classBaseUsbSerialJtag" kindref="compound">BaseUsbSerialJtag</ref></computeroutput>, upper layers stay portable to alternate transports (host-side mock, future USB-CDC OTG implementation, etc.).</para>
</simplesect>
<simplesect kind="par"><title>Coexistence with the IDF console</title><para>If <computeroutput>CONFIG_ESP_CONSOLE_USB_SERIAL_JTAG=y</computeroutput>, the IDF console driver is already installed before <computeroutput>app_main</computeroutput> runs and <computeroutput>usb_serial_jtag_is_driver_installed()</computeroutput> returns true. <computeroutput>Initialize()</computeroutput> detects this and treats the controller as already-good without calling <computeroutput>usb_serial_jtag_driver_install()</computeroutput> a second time (which would return <computeroutput>ESP_ERR_INVALID_STATE</computeroutput>). In that mode, the IDF <computeroutput>printf</computeroutput> / <computeroutput>ESP_LOG</computeroutput> infrastructure shares the controller with this wrapper; both paths push to the same TX ring without conflict.</para>
</simplesect>
<simplesect kind="par"><title>Thread safety</title><para>The Espressif driver supports concurrent reader and writer tasks. This wrapper holds no internal state beyond <computeroutput>initialized_</computeroutput> after <computeroutput>Initialize()</computeroutput>, so multiple writer tasks may call <computeroutput>Write()</computeroutput> concurrently. If you call <computeroutput>Read()</computeroutput> from more than one task, hold an external mutex.</para>
</simplesect>
<simplesect kind="par"><title>Singleton helper</title><para>Most boards only ever need one instance (the controller is a single silicon block). Use <computeroutput><ref refid="classEspUsbSerialJtag_1a60ddfcf0685c26824d48464efc83853a" kindref="member">EspUsbSerialJtag::Default()</ref></computeroutput> to grab a process-wide shared instance configured with the supplied <computeroutput>config</computeroutput> on first call.</para>
</simplesect>
